# Why Cleanup?

Some effects create ongoing resources: event listeners, timers, WebSocket connections. If you don't clean them up when the component unmounts or before the effect runs again, you'll get memory leaks and bugs.

You can return a **cleanup function** from your effect. React will call it:

* Before the component unmounts.
* Before re-running the effect (if dependencies changed).

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    console.log('Tick');
  }, 1000);

  // Cleanup
  return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, []);
```

slides.codeSnippet:
useEffect(() => {
  const handleResize = () => {
    console.log('Window resized');
  };
  window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

  // Cleanup
  return () => {
    window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  };
}, []); // Only on mount/unmount
